The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Calcutta University has decided to abolish the system of admitting students to the bachelor in business administration (BBA) course through a common test. From the current academic year, the colleges will be able to follow their own procedure in admitting students to the first-year BBA course. The decision was taken at the university?s undergraduate council meeting, a senior official said on Sunday.

 Seven persons were injured in a clash in Mathpukur, Tiljala, over supply of building material to a housing project. At least three houses were damaged. The shops in a local market downed shutters after the incident as a mark of protest. Later, a police picket was posted in the neighbourhood. Police said several bombs were hurled and bullets fired. No one has been arrested. 

 Prakash Dutta, 29, a resident of Dum Dum, drowned on Sunday afternoon while bathing with his friends in the sea at New Digha. Raja Mukherjee, officer-in-charge of Digha police station, said Dutta?s body was fished out in the evening and sent for post-mortem.

 The city civic authorities will observe Tagore?s birth anniversary, on May 9, by organising a programme in Town Hall. Artists who are likely to perform at the programme include Dwijen Mukhopadhyay, Suchitra Mitra, Purabi Mukhopadhyay, Sreeradha Bandopadhyay, Indrani Sen, Partha Ghosh and Gouri Ghosh. Municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay said the venue had hosted Tagore?s 50th birth anniversary programme in 1912 and also a civic reception accorded to the poet on his 70th birthday in 1931. 

 Large parts of Dum Dum, Motijheel and Nagerbazar, on the northern fringes of the city, were without power since Friday evening, after a 6-kv high-tension feeder tripped. On Saturday, another transformer collapsed after developing a snag. Local residents demonstrated in front of the local CESC office and also blocked roads on Friday and Saturday, demanding immediate restoration of supply. CESC officials said repairs were being undertaken ?on a war footing?.

 A large number of employees of Calcutta University have submitted a memorandum to vice-chancellor Asis Kumar Banerjee listing a number of demands, an official said on Sunday. The demands include introduction of career advancement schemes on a par with state government employees. 

 Thirty children from various schools in Manipur will meet senior officers of the army at Fort William on Monday. An army spokesperson said on Sunday that the interactive session was aimed at improving the attitude of the people in the Northeast towards the armed forces.

 Power supply to Tiljala may be disrupted on Wednesday because of maintenance work on the CESC transmission lines in the area. An official of the power utility said repairs will be undertaken to upgrade the ?primary voltage supply?. 

 The Couriers Agents? Association of India (Eastern zone) on Sunday threatened to launch an agitation to protest the recent amendment to the Postal Act, barring private couriers from delivering parcels weighing less than 300 g. 

